Turkey Equity Movers: Banvit, Fenerbahce, TSKB, Turk Telekom

-- B y   B e n j a m i n   H a r v e y
-- 
2011-07-04T15:34:09Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-04/turkey-equity-movers-banvit-fenerbahce-tskb-turk-telekom.html
Turkey ’s benchmark  ISE National 100
Index (XU100)  gained 922.22, or 1.5 percent, to 64,186.73 at the 5:30
p.m. close in Istanbul, its highest since June 7.  The following stocks were active. Symbols are in
parentheses.  Banvit Bandirma Vitaminli Yem Sanayii AS (BANVT TI), a
poultry producer, rose 3.2 percent to a one-month high of 4.54
liras after shareholder Valid Faruk Ebubekir signed a
preliminary agreement to sell 16.3 million shares at 4.8 liras
each to the  United Arab Emirates ’ Aabar Investments PJSC.  Fenerbahce Sportif Hizmetler Sanayi & Ticaret AS (FENER
TI), the licensing and merchandising arm of last year’s Turkish
soccer league champion Fenerbahce, plunged 13.75 liras, or 19
percent, to 57.5 liras after Bloomberg HT television reported 50
people including Fenerbahce chairman Aziz Yildirim were arrested
on charges of involvement in a match-fixing ring.  Shares linked to second-place side Trabzonspor (TSPOR TI)
retreated 7.56 percent to 16.50 liras.  Besiktas Futbol Yatirimlari Sanayi & Ticaret AS (BJKAS TI)
sank 6.7 percent to 9.56 liras while Istanbul rival Galatasaray
Sportif Sinai & Ticaret Yatirimlar AS (GRSAY TI) dropped 3.7
percent to 362 liras.  Turkiye Sinai Kalkinma Bankasi AS (TSKB)  , a Turkish
investment bank known as TSKB, gained 8 kurus, or 3.1 percent,
to 2.67 liras, its highest in more than a month. TSKB will get a
75 million-euro portion ($109 million) of the European
Investment Bank loans under the Treasury’s guarantee to lend to
companies, the bank said in a statement to the  Istanbul Stock
Exchange  today.  Turk Telekomunikasyon AS (TTKOM)  , Turkey’s largest phone
company, surged in heavy trading during the last minute before
the market closed, gaining 86 kurus, or 10 percent, to 9.38
liras, an all-time high and record advance.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Benjamin Harvey in Istanbul at 
